<p>Cominciamo bene. [<a href="#identifier_101_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_102_80959" class="footnote">It can, for the simple reason that the paralogy here presented ammounts to nothing besides "I who pretend to judge whether '''the world''' is good or bad nevertheless have no control over my own actions, and you're supposed to think this fails to disqualify me from my lofty self-assigned station because if you do I'll reciprocally agree it doesn't disqualify you, either". The value which the left lobe of that agreement provides is central to his stance ; but whatever residue (if any) the right lobe provides to me is scarcely worth the notice. I couldn't care less what he agrees to or doesn't ; yet it is this very trade whereby both Englishman and Indian have their rights (specifically and strictly to the anglo-culture and attendant commercial world) "equally" recognized that is not in any sense neutral, but on the contrary : it strictly reduces to cultural assimilation. The proposition of the moron that he wouldn't be a moron if we were morons too is scant defense, and the re-dressed exercise here on display fares no better -- it so happens that I do not particularly wish to be assimilated by my inferiors.</p>
<p>That Lewis does not see this, in spite of having earlier made plentiful proof of his capacity to see points just as fine or finer on his own power, indicates as plainly as can be desired the dulling, the stupefying effect of "faith" in thinking humans. You're dumber for being an xtian, and nothing else. [<a href="#identifier_102_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_103_80959" class="footnote">He'd have perhaps made a great engineer, "if Lit. Hum. didn't hang him first". [<a href="#identifier_103_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_104_80959" class="footnote">It's not necessarily either pessimism or cowardice. Having a certain line past which life's not worth living is the fundamental construct upon which what is known as "a man" is built, the cornerstone of manhood so to speak. [<a href="#identifier_104_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_105_80959" class="footnote">Ah, okay, thankfully. It was pretty atrocious to go through. [<a href="#identifier_105_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_106_80959" class="footnote">Usually "Conchobar", mythical king of Ulster. Supposedly he was conceived through the rather trite methodology of his mother asking a seer "what's it an auspicious time for ?" and the seer retorting that it was an auspicious time for conceiving a king out of a queen. [<a href="#identifier_106_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_107_80959" class="footnote">To this day the scent of a certain crawling sweet pea kin is my favourite perfume. [<a href="#identifier_107_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-back-link">&#8617;</a>]</li><li id="footnote_108_80959" class="footnote">I've indeed not have grasped any such thing ; the contrary, Lewis Sr. was the fool of all time. [<a href="#identifier_108_80959" class="footnote-link footnote-ba